Open the following code in an SWT project:

The resulting behavior is three copies of visuals of the "Hello" label, and two
copies of "Push Me" button shows up on the canvas.  The label and the button
both show up twice on the beans view.

It appears that this behavior is caused by having the dispose listener in the code.


------
import org.eclipse.swt.events.DisposeEvent;

public class Copies {
	private org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell sShell = null;  //  @jve:visual-info 
decl-index=0 visual-constraint="20,25"
	private org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Label label = null;
	private org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Button button = null;
	/**
	 * This method initializes sShell	
	 *
	 */    
	private void createSShell () {
		sShell = new org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell ();		   
		button = new org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Button(sShell,org.eclipse.swt.SWT.NONE);
		label = new org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Label(sShell,org.eclipse.swt.SWT.NONE);
		sShell.setSize(new org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Point(442,267));
		sShell.setLayout(new org.eclipse.swt.layout.RowLayout());
		button.setText("Push Me");
		final org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Color ivjColor1 = new
org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Color(org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display.getDefault(),
238, 51, 54);
		button.setForeground(ivjColor1);
		label.setText("Hello");
		final org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Font ivjFont1 = new
org.eclipse.swt.graphics.Font(org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display.getDefault(),
"Comic Sans MS", 14, org.eclipse.swt.SWT.BOLD); 
		label.setFont(ivjFont1);
		sShell.addDisposeListener(new org.eclipse.swt.events.DisposeListener() {
			public void widgetDisposed(DisposeEvent arg0) {
				ivjColor1.dispose();
				ivjFont1.dispose();
			}
		});
	}
 }
